page.title: 20WILDLIFE:NORTH NORFOLK
page.content: {WILDLIFE IN NORTH NORFOLK Again because this is a coastal area a great variety of birds find their way into local gardens,especialy at Spring and Autumn migrations.For example, parties of Goldcrests are usually seen in spring,and in severe weather Snipe, Water Rail,Redshank and Lapwing have all been reported to have come into gardens from their usual territory. Butterflies are numerous,the more common species such as Red Admiral, Peacock,Brimstone and Tortoiseshell are always present.Painted Ladies are sometimes seen and in the past Swallow tail and Camberwell Beauty have been reported.In most years Humming-bird, Hawkmoth are present.Despite the reported general decline of the frog and toad population the area seems to have its fair share of both,and adders which are plentiful in the dunes.
